[3] Dominican Republic
Date: 25 Sep 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Prensa Latina [edited]
<http://www.plenglish.com/article.asp?ID=%7B6B71045C-0FB5-4F9C-A636-FA0F04CC1A6A%7D)&language=EN>

Dengue Deaths in Dominican Republic
-------------------------------------------
The dengue epidemic ravaging the Dominican Republic has raised the
death toll to 37 and filled hospital emergency rooms, although health
authorities say it is declining.
Two additional people died this weekend, a man of 33 and a 6-year-old
girl, but officially neither death has been confirmed as dengue yet.
The State Health Secretary, Bautista Rojas, insisted that the trend
[in dengue cases] is decreasing, since of 2180 patients that have
received [medical] attention Saturday [23 Sep 2006] up to early on
Sunday [24 Sep 2006] in the capital, only 38 have been considered
[dengue] infected.
With this last figure, cases reported by hospitals rose to 3562,
despite a national campaign to eliminate the 2.5 million possible
sources of the mosquito _Aedes aegypti_, the transmitter of this disease.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[It would be interesting to know how many of the current cases are
dengue fever and how many are dengue hemorrhagic fever and which
serotype(s) is (are) involved in this year's 2006 outbreak. - Mod.TY]

